@gmkurtzer You're right:

On the F25 VM:
```
[vagrant@localhost ~]$ /lib64/libc.so.6 --version
GNU C Library (GNU libc) stable release version 2.24, by Roland McGrath et al.
[cut]
[vagrant@localhost ~]$ cat test.c 
#include &lt;stdlib.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
int main(){
    printf("Doing a non-null setenv...\n");
    int g_rc = setenv("good_test", "1", 1);
    printf("non-null setenv returned: %d\n", g_rc);
    printf("Doing a NULL setenv...\n");
    int b_rc = setenv("env_test", NULL, 1);
    printf("NULL setenv returned: %d\n", b_rc);
    return 0;

}
[vagrant@localhost ~]$ gcc test.c 
[vagrant@localhost ~]$ ./a.out 
Doing a non-null setenv...
non-null setenv returned: 0
Doing a NULL setenv...
Segmentation fault (core dumped)
```

On a SLES12 box:
```~&gt; /lib64/libc.so.6 --version
GNU C Library (GNU libc) stable release version 2.19 (git 9a869d822025), by Roland McGrath et al.
[cut]
~&gt; gcc test.c         
~&gt; ./a.out 
Doing a non-null setenv...
non-null setenv returned: 0
Doing a NULL setenv...
NULL setenv returned: 0
```

In all cases, gcc will return some kind of warning:
```gcc -Wall envtest.c 
envtest.c: In function 'main':
envtest.c:8:5: warning: null argument where non-null required (argument 2) [-Wnonnull]
     int b_rc = setenv("env_test", NULL, 1);
     ^
```
Tried on a RHEL box running glibc 2.12, also no segfault.
Not sure if this is a bug or a "feature" on libc's part, or what should be done on singularity's part

